Mr Joel Ssenyonyi, who speaks for NUP, said going to court is just one of the many options available to them.
Agents’ arrests
He, however, said that the challenge they have met with this option is that the police and other security agencies are arresting their agents who had gathered some of the evidence that would be used in the court.
“We are still gathering evidence. As soon as we are ready, we shall let Ugandans know our next plan of action. But the regime doesn’t want us to have this evidence. They are arresting people with the correct declaration of results forms like anybody who has something to hide will do,” Mr Ssenyonyi said.
According to the 2017 Constitutional Amendment of Article 104 (2), a presidential candidate aggrieved with the results of an election has up to 15 days from the date of the declaration of results to file a petition at the Supreme Court. The amendment also gives the Supreme Court up to 45 days to determine the petition.



