}



Mr Patrick Amuriat Oboi, who was the party’s presidential candidate, even called upon Mr Kyagulanyi not to take that course of action because it will end in the same way previous petitions have ended.
What legal minds say
Mr Ibrahim Kivumbi Kaboggoza, a senior partner at Kivumbi, Madina and Kikomeko Advocates and Solicitors, agrees that the current configuration of the judicial system is not the best that anyone aggrieved with the results of presidential elections should go to. However, not doing so, Kivumbi says, denies the country the opportunity to taste some actions and inactions of the Electoral Commission and other players.
“Court works on evidence. But as you already know, security is arresting people who are gathering declaration forms which are needed to show the impact that the irregularities had on the final outcome. So, such things make it hard to challenge presidential results. But otherwise, we would have loved to hear the court pronounce itself on issues like the torture of candidates and their agents, going with cameras at polling stations, among others,” Kivumbi said.
Appointment of judges
Asked about why it is hard for the court to annul a presidential election in Uganda, Kivumbi pointed to the appointment of judges.



